-- 1. OSI Model
UPDATE topic_content SET
  osi_layer = 'All Layers',
  theory_md = E'## The OSI Model\n\nThe Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) model is a conceptual framework that standardises how different network systems communicate. Published by ISO in 1984, it divides the communication process into seven distinct layers, each with a specific role. Understanding OSI is foundational to diagnosing problems, understanding protocols, and designing networks.\n\n### The Seven Layers\n\n**Layer 7 — Application**\nThe layer closest to the end user. It provides the interface between the network and the application software. Protocols here include HTTP/HTTPS (web), SMTP/IMAP (email), FTP (file transfer), DNS (name resolution), DHCP, and SSH. The Application layer does not refer to the application itself — it refers to the services the network provides to applications.\n\n**Layer 6 — Presentation**\nResponsible for data translation, encryption, and compression. It ensures that data sent from the Application layer of one system is readable by the Application layer of another. TLS/SSL encryption happens here. JPEG, MPEG, and ASCII are presentation-layer formats.\n\n**Layer 5 — Session**\nManages and controls the connections (sessions) between computers. It establishes, maintains, and terminates sessions. NetBIOS, RPC, and SQL sessions operate here. It handles checkpointing and recovery so a long file transfer can resume after a disruption.\n\n**Layer 4 — Transport**\nProvides reliable (TCP) or best-effort (UDP) delivery of data between hosts. Segments data from the upper layers, adds source and destination port numbers, and handles flow control and error recovery. **TCP** uses a three-way handshake, sequence numbers, and acknowledgements. **UDP** is connectionless and faster — used for DNS, DHCP, video streaming, and VoIP.\n\n**Layer 3 — Network**\nHandles logical addressing (IP addresses) and routing between networks. Routers operate at this layer. IP, ICMP, ARP, and routing protocols (OSPF, BGP) are Layer 3. This layer determines the best path for a packet to travel from source to destination across multiple networks.\n\n**Layer 2 — Data Link**\nTransfers data between directly connected nodes — node-to-node delivery. Switches operate here. It uses MAC addresses to identify devices on the same network segment. Divided into two sublayers: **LLC** (Logical Link Control) and **MAC** (Media Access Control). Protocols include Ethernet (802.3), Wi-Fi (802.11), PPP, and VLANs (802.1Q).\n\n**Layer 1 — Physical**\nThe actual transmission of raw bits over a physical medium — cables, connectors, voltages, light pulses, and radio waves. Hubs, repeaters, and NICs operate here. Standards include IEEE 802.3 (Ethernet cabling), RS-232, and DSL.\n\n### Encapsulation and Decapsulation\n\nWhen data travels down the OSI stack from sender to receiver, each layer **adds a header** (and sometimes a trailer) — this is **encapsulation**. When the data arrives and travels back up the stack, each layer **strips its header** — this is **decapsulation**.\n\n| Layer | PDU Name | Added Info |\n|-------|----------|------------|\n| 4 | Segment / Datagram | Port numbers, seq numbers |\n| 3 | Packet | Source/dest IP addresses |\n| 2 | Frame | Source/dest MAC, FCS |\n| 1 | Bits | Signal encoding |\n\n### Mnemonic\n\n**Top-down (7→1):** All People Seem To Need Data Processing\n**Bottom-up (1→7):** Please Do Not Throw Sausage Pizza Away\n\n### OSI vs TCP/IP\n\nThe OSI model is the reference model. The TCP/IP model (what the internet actually uses) collapses OSI into 4 layers: Application (OSI 5-7), Transport (OSI 4), Internet (OSI 3), and Network Access (OSI 1-2). In the real world, engineers use OSI for troubleshooting but TCP/IP describes actual implementation.\n\n### Why OSI Matters for CCNA\n\nNetwork problems almost always occur at a specific layer. A systematic bottom-up troubleshooting approach — Physical → Data Link → Network → Transport → Application — isolates the root cause efficiently. When a Cisco engineer says "that is a Layer 2 issue," they mean a MAC/switching/VLAN/STP problem rather than a routing (L3) or cable (L1) problem.',
  practical_md = E'## Troubleshooting with the OSI Model\n\nThe most powerful use of OSI is structured troubleshooting. Always start at Layer 1 and work up — there is no point checking routing if the cable is unplugged.\n\n### Bottom-Up Approach\n\n**Layer 1 — Physical checks:**\n- Is the cable plugged in? Check both ends.\n- Is the link light on (solid = link, blinking = activity)?\n- `show interfaces Gi0/0` — look for "line protocol is up"\n- Line protocol down = L1 or L2 problem\n\n**Layer 2 — Data Link checks:**\n- Is the MAC address in the switch table? `show mac address-table`\n- Is STP blocking the port? `show spanning-tree`\n- Are VLANs configured correctly? `show vlan brief`\n- Duplex mismatch causes CRC errors — `show interfaces` for errors\n\n**Layer 3 — Network checks:**\n- Can you ping the default gateway?\n- Is there a route? `show ip route`\n- Is the interface IP correct? `show ip interface brief`\n- Are ACLs blocking? `show access-lists`\n\n**Layer 4 — Transport checks:**\n- Is the destination port open and listening?\n- Is a firewall blocking the TCP/UDP port?\n- `show ip nat translations` — NAT translating correctly?\n\n**Layer 7 — Application checks:**\n- Is DNS resolving? `nslookup hostname`\n- Is the service running on the server?\n- Is the correct URL/hostname being used?\n\n### OSI Troubleshooting Examples\n\n**Scenario:** PC cannot reach the internet.\n1. Ping 127.0.0.1 → Tests L3/L4 stack on PC itself\n2. Ping default gateway (e.g. 192.168.1.1) → Tests L1/L2/L3 to router\n3. Ping 8.8.8.8 → Tests routing beyond the LAN\n4. Ping google.com → Tests DNS (L7)\n\nIf step 3 works but step 4 fails → DNS problem (L7), not routing.',
  key_commands = '["show interfaces", "show ip interface brief", "show mac address-table", "show spanning-tree", "show vlan brief", "show ip route", "show access-lists", "ping", "traceroute"]'::jsonb,
  common_mistakes = '["Confusing the OSI model (7 layers) with the TCP/IP model (4 layers)", "Thinking routers are Layer 2 devices — routers are Layer 3", "Forgetting that switches operate at Layer 2 (not Layer 1 like hubs)", "Assuming Layer 7 is the application itself — it is the network services the app uses", "Skipping layers when troubleshooting instead of working bottom-up"]'::jsonb
WHERE topic_id = (SELECT id FROM topics WHERE slug = 'osi-model');

-- 2. Network Types
UPDATE topic_content SET
  osi_layer = 'All Layers',
  theory_md = E'## Network Types\n\nNetworks are classified by their geographic scope, ownership model, and technology. Understanding these distinctions is essential for designing, managing, and troubleshooting infrastructure at the right scale.\n\n### PAN — Personal Area Network\n\nThe smallest network type, spanning a few metres around a single person. Connects personal devices — smartphones, laptops, wireless earbuds, smartwatches. Technologies: Bluetooth (802.15.1), Zigbee, NFC, USB. Typical range: 1–10 metres. No infrastructure required — ad-hoc device-to-device.\n\n### LAN — Local Area Network\n\nCovers a single building, floor, or campus. Owned and operated by the organisation using it. The most common network type in enterprise IT. Technologies: Ethernet (802.3) at 1/10/25/40/100 Gbps, Wi-Fi (802.11). Typical distance: up to 100 metres per copper segment. Latency: sub-millisecond. Devices: switches, access points, routers at the edge.\n\n**Key LAN characteristics:**\n- High bandwidth (1–100 Gbps)\n- Low latency (< 1ms)\n- Private ownership\n- Typically uses RFC 1918 private addresses (10.x, 172.16-31.x, 192.168.x)\n\n### WLAN — Wireless LAN\n\nA LAN where the access medium is radio rather than copper or fibre. Uses IEEE 802.11 standards (Wi-Fi). WLAN extends LAN connectivity without cabling. Range: 30–100m indoors. An access point (AP) bridges wireless clients onto the wired LAN. WLANs are logically part of a LAN — the distinction is physical medium only.\n\n### MAN — Metropolitan Area Network\n\nCovers a city or metropolitan region — typically 5–50 km. Connects multiple LANs across a city. Often built and operated by ISPs or municipalities. Technologies: Metro Ethernet, SONET/SDH, fibre rings. Example: connecting a bank headquarters to its branches across a city. Bandwidth: 1 Gbps to 100 Gbps.\n\n### WAN — Wide Area Network\n\nSpans countries, continents, or the globe. Connects geographically separated LANs. Typically leased from a service provider. Technologies: MPLS, leased lines, SD-WAN, VPN over internet. Bandwidth: historically lower than LAN (1–100 Mbps), but modern WAN can reach 100 Gbps on fibre. Higher latency due to distance (10–150ms transcontinental).\n\n**Common WAN technologies:**\n- **MPLS**: Provider-managed, label-switched, reliable QoS\n- **Leased line**: Dedicated point-to-point circuit\n- **SD-WAN**: Software-defined overlay over cheap internet links\n- **IPsec VPN**: Encrypted tunnel over public internet\n\n### The Internet\n\nThe Internet is the world largest WAN — but it is not owned by any single entity. It is a network of networks: tens of thousands of autonomous systems (AS) interconnected via BGP (Border Gateway Protocol). Your ISP connects your LAN to their network, which peers with other ISPs, forming a global mesh.\n\n### SAN — Storage Area Network\n\nA specialised network dedicated to connecting servers to storage arrays. Appears to servers as locally-attached storage. Technologies: Fibre Channel (FC), iSCSI over Ethernet. High bandwidth, extremely low latency. Common in data centres.\n\n### Network Type Comparison\n\n| Type | Scope | Speed | Latency | Owner |\n|------|-------|-------|---------|-------|\n| PAN | < 10m | < 3 Mbps | Low | Personal |\n| LAN | Building | 1–100 Gbps | < 1ms | Organisation |\n| WLAN | Building | 600 Mbps–9.6 Gbps | Low | Organisation |\n| MAN | City | 1–100 Gbps | Low–Med | ISP/City |\n| WAN | Country/Globe | 1 Mbps–100 Gbps | Med–High | ISP |\n| Internet | Global | Varies | 10–150ms | None (federated) |',
  practical_md = E'## Identifying Network Types in the Real World\n\nNetwork type classification matters when designing solutions, sizing connections, and setting latency expectations.\n\n### Decision Framework\n\n- All devices in one building? → **LAN**\n- Devices connected wirelessly in a building? → **WLAN** (logically still a LAN)\n- Connecting two offices in the same city? → **MAN** or **WAN**\n- Connecting offices across different countries? → **WAN**\n- Internet connectivity? → **WAN** (to ISP), then the **Internet**\n- Bluetooth headset to phone? → **PAN**\n\n### Enterprise WAN Design Choices\n\n**MPLS (legacy):** Reliable, QoS-capable, expensive. Still dominant in regulated industries (banking, healthcare).\n\n**SD-WAN (modern):** Routes traffic dynamically across multiple cheaper internet links. Reduces cost while maintaining application performance. Major vendors: Cisco Viptela, VMware Velocloud, Fortinet.\n\n**IPsec VPN:** Lowest cost — encrypts traffic over standard internet. Best for smaller sites or backup connectivity.\n\n### Common Interview/Exam Traps\n\n- WLAN is not a WAN — it is wireless *LAN*\n- WAN does not mean slow — modern WAN can be faster than some LANs\n- The Internet is technically a WAN but is always referred to as "the Internet"\n- A VPN is not a network type — it is a technology that creates a virtual private network *over* a WAN/Internet',
  key_commands = '["show interfaces", "show ip interface brief", "traceroute", "ping"]'::jsonb,
  common_mistakes = '["Confusing WLAN (wireless LAN) with WAN — they are completely different", "Thinking WAN always means slow — modern MPLS/fibre WAN is very fast", "Treating the Internet as a single network — it is thousands of interconnected ASes", "Forgetting SAN exists — important in data centre contexts"]'::jsonb
WHERE topic_id = (SELECT id FROM topics WHERE slug = 'network-types');

-- 3. Network Topologies
UPDATE topic_content SET
  osi_layer = 'Layer 1–2',
  theory_md = E'## Network Topologies\n\nA network topology describes how devices are physically or logically arranged and interconnected. Choosing the right topology involves trade-offs between cost, redundancy, performance, and scalability. Physical topology is how cables are actually run; logical topology is how data flows regardless of physical layout.\n\n### Bus Topology\n\nAll devices share a single cable (the "bus"). Data is broadcast to all devices — only the intended recipient processes it. A break anywhere on the cable takes down the entire network.\n\n**Characteristics:**\n- Simple and cheap to install\n- Single point of failure (the bus cable)\n- Collisions possible — only one device can transmit at a time (CSMA/CD)\n- Maximum cable length limits\n- **Status: Obsolete.** Used in early 10BASE2/10BASE5 Ethernet. Not used in modern networks.\n\n### Ring Topology\n\nDevices are connected in a closed loop. Data travels around the ring in one direction (or both in dual-ring). Token Ring (IEEE 802.5) and FDDI use this topology.\n\n**Characteristics:**\n- Predictable performance — token passing prevents collisions\n- A single break can take down the ring (dual-ring mitigates this)\n- Adding/removing devices disrupts the ring\n- **Status: Obsolete** for LANs. SONET/SDH WAN rings still used in carrier networks.\n\n### Star Topology\n\nAll devices connect to a central device (switch or hub). The most common modern LAN topology. If one cable fails, only that device is affected. If the central switch fails, the entire segment goes down.\n\n**Characteristics:**\n- Easy to troubleshoot (isolate one cable/port at a time)\n- Easy to add/remove devices without disruption\n- Central device is a single point of failure\n- Requires more cable than bus\n- **Status: The standard for modern LANs.** Every access layer switch is a star.\n\n### Extended Star (Hierarchical Star)\n\nStar topologies connected together — switches connecting to distribution switches, which connect to a core. This is the Cisco three-tier hierarchical model (Access → Distribution → Core). The dominant enterprise LAN design.\n\n### Mesh Topology\n\nEvery device connects directly to every other device. Provides maximum redundancy — any single link failure does not isolate any device.\n\n**Full mesh:** n(n-1)/2 links for n devices. A 10-device full mesh requires 45 links. Does not scale.\n\n**Partial mesh:** Only critical paths are redundant. Practical compromise between redundancy and cost.\n\n**Characteristics:**\n- Maximum redundancy and resilience\n- Full mesh is expensive and complex to manage\n- **Status:** Full mesh used in WAN (ISP backbone, data centre interconnects). Partial mesh common in distribution/core layers.\n\n### Point-to-Point\n\nA dedicated link between exactly two devices. All WAN leased lines and serial links are point-to-point. Simple, predictable, secure.\n\n### Hybrid Topology\n\nMost real-world networks combine topologies. A typical enterprise uses:\n- **Star** at the access layer (PCs to switches)\n- **Extended star / partial mesh** at distribution\n- **Full or partial mesh** at the core for redundancy\n\n### Topology and Failure Impact\n\n| Topology | Device failure impact | Link failure impact | Scalability |\n|----------|----------------------|---------------------|-------------|\n| Bus | Entire network | Entire network | Poor |\n| Ring | Entire network (single) | Entire network | Poor |\n| Star | One device | One device | Good |\n| Full mesh | None | None | Poor |\n| Partial mesh | Varies | Varies | Medium |\n| Extended star | Subtree | Subtree | Excellent |',
  practical_md = E'## Topology Design in Practice\n\n### Cisco Three-Tier Model\n\nThe most widely deployed enterprise LAN design follows three layers:\n\n**Access layer:** Connects end devices (PCs, phones, printers, APs) to the network. Star topology. Devices: access switches. Functions: port security, VLANs, PoE, 802.1X.\n\n**Distribution layer:** Aggregates access switches. Inter-VLAN routing, QoS policy, redundant uplinks. Partial mesh to core. Devices: multilayer switches.\n\n**Core layer:** High-speed backbone connecting distribution blocks and WAN/data centre. Full or partial mesh. No policy enforcement — just fast switching. Devices: high-capacity switches/routers.\n\n### Two-Tier (Collapsed Core)\n\nSmaller networks collapse distribution and core into one layer. Common in mid-size enterprise. Reduces cost at the expense of scalability.\n\n### Spine-Leaf (Data Centre)\n\nModern data centres use a two-tier spine-leaf topology:\n- **Leaf switches** connect to servers\n- **Spine switches** connect all leaves\n- Every leaf connects to every spine (full mesh between tiers)\n- Predictable, low-latency, horizontally scalable\n\n### Topology Selection Criteria\n\n- **Number of devices:** More devices → hierarchical star or spine-leaf\n- **Redundancy required:** Mission-critical → partial or full mesh at core\n- **Budget:** Full mesh very expensive — partial mesh is a practical compromise\n- **Ease of management:** Star is easiest to troubleshoot\n- **WAN:** Almost always point-to-point or partial mesh',
  key_commands = '["show spanning-tree", "show cdp neighbors", "show interfaces status", "show ip route"]'::jsonb,
  common_mistakes = '["Thinking bus and ring topologies are still used in modern LANs — they are not", "Confusing physical and logical topology — Wi-Fi is physically a star but logically a bus (shared medium)", "Underestimating single points of failure in star topology — the central switch is critical", "Designing full mesh for large networks — n(n-1)/2 links makes this impractical past ~6 devices"]'::jsonb
WHERE topic_id = (SELECT id FROM topics WHERE slug = 'network-topologies');

-- 4. Network Devices
UPDATE topic_content SET
  osi_layer = 'Layer 1–3',
  theory_md = E'## Network Devices\n\nEvery device in a network operates at one or more layers of the OSI model. Understanding which layer a device operates at tells you what it can "see" (MAC vs IP vs ports) and what it can do (repeat, switch, route, filter).\n\n### Hub — Layer 1\n\nA hub is a multi-port repeater. It receives a signal on one port and broadcasts it to all other ports — every connected device sees every frame. Hubs create a single collision domain: only one device can transmit at a time (CSMA/CD). They have no intelligence — no MAC table, no traffic management.\n\n**Status: Obsolete.** Replaced entirely by switches. You may still see hubs in exam questions as a "what not to use" example.\n\n### Switch — Layer 2\n\nThe most important access-layer device. A switch learns MAC addresses and forwards frames only to the correct port — dramatically reducing unnecessary traffic. Each port is its own collision domain. A switch maintains a **MAC address table** (CAM table) mapping MAC addresses to ports.\n\n**How a switch learns:** When a frame arrives, the switch records the source MAC and incoming port. If the destination MAC is unknown, it floods to all ports (except the source). Once learned, future frames are forwarded directly.\n\n**Key switch features:**\n- **VLANs:** Segment the network into isolated broadcast domains\n- **STP:** Prevents Layer 2 loops\n- **Port security:** Restrict which MACs can use a port\n- **PoE:** Power over Ethernet for APs, IP phones, cameras\n- **Trunking:** 802.1Q trunk links carry multiple VLANs\n\n### Multilayer Switch (L3 Switch) — Layer 2 + 3\n\nA Layer 3 switch combines switching and routing in hardware. It can route between VLANs (inter-VLAN routing via SVIs) without needing a separate router. Routing is done in hardware ASICs — much faster than a software-based router for local traffic. Used at the distribution and core layers.\n\n### Router — Layer 3\n\nRouters connect different networks using IP addresses. They maintain routing tables and make per-packet forwarding decisions based on destination IP. Every router interface is its own broadcast domain.\n\n**Router functions:**\n- Routing between networks (LAN to WAN, VLAN to VLAN via ROAS)\n- NAT/PAT — translating private IPs to public\n- DHCP server for connected subnets\n- ACL enforcement — filtering by IP/port\n- WAN connectivity — serial, DSL, fibre handoffs\n- Dynamic routing protocols (OSPF, BGP, EIGRP)\n\n### Firewall — Layer 3–7\n\nFilters traffic based on state, IP, port, and application. A **stateful firewall** tracks the state of TCP sessions — it knows if a packet is part of an established connection or a new unsolicited inbound attempt. Next-generation firewalls (NGFW) inspect application layer content (Layer 7).\n\n**Zones:** Firewalls divide the network into security zones — typically Inside (trusted LAN), Outside (internet), and DMZ (servers reachable from internet but isolated from LAN).\n\n### Wireless Access Point (AP) — Layer 2\n\nBridges wireless clients (802.11) to the wired LAN (802.3). Operates at Layer 2 — it is essentially a wireless switch port. Standalone APs configure themselves. Enterprise APs are managed by a Wireless LAN Controller (WLC) via CAPWAP tunnels — centralising RF management, roaming, and policy.\n\n### Wireless LAN Controller (WLC) — Layer 2–3\n\nCentrally manages all APs in an enterprise. APs in "lightweight" mode forward all client traffic to the WLC via CAPWAP. The WLC handles authentication (802.1X), SSID/VLAN mapping, RF channel/power management, and seamless roaming.\n\n### IDS / IPS — Layer 3–7\n\n**IDS** (Intrusion Detection System) monitors traffic and alerts on suspicious patterns — passive, does not block. **IPS** (Intrusion Prevention System) sits inline and can block malicious traffic in real time. Often integrated into NGFWs.\n\n### Device Layer Summary\n\n| Device | OSI Layer | Addressing | Broadcast Domain |\n|--------|-----------|------------|------------------|\n| Hub | 1 | None | Shared |\n| Switch | 2 | MAC | Per VLAN |\n| L3 Switch | 2–3 | MAC + IP | Per VLAN/SVI |\n| Router | 3 | IP | Per interface |\n| Firewall | 3–7 | IP + Port | Per zone |\n| AP | 2 | MAC | Shared (wireless) |\n| WLC | 2–3 | MAC + IP | Per SSID/VLAN |',
  practical_md = E'## Device Selection and Placement\n\n### When to use what\n\n**Access layer (connecting end devices):**\nUse a Layer 2 access switch. Add PoE capability if deploying IP phones or wireless APs. Enable port security and 802.1X for security.\n\n**Distribution layer (aggregating access):**\nUse a multilayer switch (L3 switch) for inter-VLAN routing. Redundant uplinks to core. HSRP/VRRP for gateway redundancy.\n\n**Core layer (backbone):**\nHigh-capacity L3 switches or routers. Speed and low latency over features.\n\n**WAN edge:**\nRouter with firewall functionality (or dedicated firewall appliance behind the router). NAT, BGP/OSPF to ISP, VPN termination.\n\n**Wireless:**\nDeploy APs in lightweight mode with a central WLC for any deployment > 5 APs. Standalone mode only for home/very small office.\n\n### Key Verification Commands\n\n```\n! Switch — check learned MACs\nshow mac address-table\n\n! Switch — check port status\nshow interfaces status\n\n! Router — check routing table\nshow ip route\n\n! Router/Switch — check interface IPs\nshow ip interface brief\n\n! Check CDP neighbors (discover adjacent devices)\nshow cdp neighbors detail\n\n! Wireless — check AP association\nshow dot11 associations\n```\n\n### Common Deployment Mistakes\n\nConnecting two switches with a straight-through cable (before Auto-MDIX) — use crossover or rely on Auto-MDIX. Plugging a PC into a trunk port. Forgetting to create VLANs on the switch before assigning ports.',
  key_commands = '["show mac address-table", "show interfaces status", "show ip route", "show ip interface brief", "show cdp neighbors detail", "show spanning-tree", "show vlan brief"]'::jsonb,
  common_mistakes = '["Thinking hub and switch are the same — hubs broadcast everything, switches are intelligent", "Forgetting L3 switches can route — they do not always need a separate router for inter-VLAN routing", "Confusing collision domain (per switch port) with broadcast domain (per VLAN/router interface)", "Thinking firewalls are just routers with ACLs — stateful inspection is fundamentally different", "Deploying APs in standalone mode for large deployments — use a WLC for anything enterprise-scale"]'::jsonb
WHERE topic_id = (SELECT id FROM topics WHERE slug = 'network-devices');

-- 5. Cables & Transmission
UPDATE topic_content SET
  osi_layer = 'Layer 1',
  theory_md = E'## Cables and Transmission Media\n\nPhysical layer media carries the raw bits that make up all network communication. Choosing the right medium involves trade-offs between distance, bandwidth, cost, EMI susceptibility, and ease of installation.\n\n### Twisted Pair Copper (UTP/STP)\n\nUnshielded Twisted Pair (UTP) is the most common LAN cabling. Pairs of copper wires are twisted together to reduce electromagnetic interference (crosstalk). Terminated with RJ-45 connectors. All modern Ethernet switches support **Auto-MDIX** — automatically negotiating straight-through vs crossover, so cable type rarely matters in practice.\n\n**UTP Categories:**\n\n| Category | Max Speed | Max Distance | Notes |\n|----------|-----------|--------------|-------|\n| Cat5e | 1 Gbps | 100m | Most common in older installs |\n| Cat6 | 10 Gbps | 55m (10G) / 100m (1G) | Standard for new installs |\n| Cat6a | 10 Gbps | 100m | Augmented Cat6, thicker, better shielding |\n| Cat8 | 25/40 Gbps | 30m | Data centre server-to-switch |\n\n**STP (Shielded Twisted Pair):** Adds metallic shielding to reduce EMI. Used in industrial environments with heavy electrical interference. More expensive and harder to install than UTP.\n\n### Fibre Optic\n\nTransmits data as pulses of light through a glass or plastic core. Immune to electromagnetic interference, supports much longer distances and higher bandwidths than copper. Two main types:\n\n**Single-Mode Fibre (SMF):**\n- Very narrow core (8–10 µm)\n- Laser light source\n- Supports distances of 10 km to 80+ km\n- Used for WAN, campus backbone, long-haul\n- More expensive transceivers (laser vs LED)\n- Yellow jacket (standard convention)\n\n**Multimode Fibre (MMF):**\n- Wider core (50–62.5 µm) — multiple light paths\n- LED or VCSEL light source\n- Shorter distances: OM3 = 300m @ 10G, OM4 = 400m @ 10G, OM5 = 150m @ 100G\n- Used for data centre and intra-building backbone\n- Less expensive transceivers\n- Orange or aqua jacket\n\n**Connectors:** LC (most common in enterprise), SC, ST, MPO (high-density multi-fibre).\n\n### Coaxial Cable\n\nA copper conductor surrounded by insulation, shielding, and outer jacket. Highly resistant to EMI. Used for cable TV (CATV), cable internet (DOCSIS), and older 10BASE2/10BASE5 Ethernet (now obsolete). Still relevant in CCTV installations and some RF applications.\n\n### Serial / WAN Cables\n\nLegacy WAN connections use serial interfaces with HDLC or PPP encapsulation. V.35 and DB60 connectors. One end is DTE (Data Terminal Equipment — the router) and the other is DCE (Data Communications Equipment — the CSU/DSU or provider device). The DCE provides the clock rate. Largely replaced by Ethernet handoffs from ISPs.\n\n### Wireless Transmission\n\nNo physical cable — uses radio frequency (RF) or infrared. IEEE 802.11 (Wi-Fi) standards:\n\n| Standard | Band | Max Speed | Notes |\n|----------|------|-----------|-------|\n| 802.11n (Wi-Fi 4) | 2.4/5 GHz | 600 Mbps | Legacy, still common |\n| 802.11ac (Wi-Fi 5) | 5 GHz | 3.5 Gbps | Current enterprise standard |\n| 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6) | 2.4/5/6 GHz | 9.6 Gbps | Latest, OFDMA, dense environments |\n\n**2.4 GHz:** Longer range, more wall penetration, but crowded (only 3 non-overlapping channels).\n**5 GHz:** Shorter range, less interference, 23+ non-overlapping channels.\n\n### Cable Selection Guide\n\n| Requirement | Recommendation |\n|-------------|----------------|\n| Standard office LAN, < 100m | Cat6 UTP |\n| High-EMI environment | Cat6a STP or fibre |\n| Data centre server links | Cat8 or MMF |\n| Intra-building backbone | OM4 MMF |\n| Campus backbone / WAN | SMF |\n| Distance > 100m, any bandwidth | Fibre (SMF or MMF) |\n\n### Straight-Through vs Crossover\n\n**Straight-through:** Same pinout on both ends (T568B). Used for unlike devices: PC-to-switch, router-to-switch.\n**Crossover:** TX pins on one end connect to RX on the other. Used for like devices: switch-to-switch, router-to-router. **Modern devices with Auto-MDIX make this distinction irrelevant** — the hardware detects and corrects automatically.\n\n**Console cable (rollover):** Connects laptop to router/switch console port for out-of-band management. Flat blue cable, RJ-45 to DB9 (or USB adapter). 9600 baud, 8N1.',
  practical_md = E'## Cable Testing and Verification\n\n### Physical Layer Verification Commands\n\n```\n! Check interface speed, duplex, errors\nshow interfaces Gi0/0\n\n! Quick status overview of all interfaces\nshow interfaces status\n\n! Check transceiver (SFP) details\nshow interfaces Gi0/1 transceiver\n```\n\n### Reading Interface Errors\n\n`show interfaces` output tells you a lot about cable/media health:\n- **Input errors / CRC errors:** Bad cable, EMI, duplex mismatch\n- **Runts:** Frames smaller than 64 bytes — collision or duplex mismatch\n- **Giants:** Frames larger than 1518 bytes — MTU mismatch\n- **Resets:** Interface flapping — loose cable or port problem\n\n### Duplex and Speed Mismatch\n\nA duplex mismatch between two connected devices (one full, one half) causes CRC errors and collisions that grow under load. Always set speed and duplex explicitly on uplinks:\n\n```\ninterface Gi0/1\n speed 1000\n duplex full\n```\n\n### Fibre Troubleshooting\n\n- **No link light:** Check Tx/Rx are not swapped (fibre is directional)\n- **Intermittent link:** Dirty connector — clean with fibre cleaning tool\n- **Wrong SFP:** SMF SFP in MMF cable will not work — match the optic to the fibre type\n- **Distance:** Check SFP rated distance against actual cable run',
  key_commands = '["show interfaces", "show interfaces status", "show interfaces Gi0/0 transceiver", "speed 1000", "duplex full"]'::jsonb,
  common_mistakes = '["Cat6 only achieves 10 Gbps at 55m, not 100m — need Cat6a for full 10G at 100m", "Confusing SMF (long distance, yellow) with MMF (short distance, orange/aqua)", "Plugging an SMF SFP into multimode fibre — optic must match fibre type", "Forgetting console cable baud rate is 9600 — not 115200 (common mistake in initial setup)", "Assuming Auto-MDIX is always available — older switches may not support it"]'::jsonb
WHERE topic_id = (SELECT id FROM topics WHERE slug = 'cables-transmission');

-- 6. Routing Fundamentals
UPDATE topic_content SET
  osi_layer = 'Layer 3',
  theory_md = E'## Routing Fundamentals\n\nRouting is the process of forwarding packets from source to destination across one or more networks. Routers make per-packet forwarding decisions by consulting a routing table — a database of known networks and the paths to reach them.\n\n### How a Router Forwards a Packet\n\n1. Packet arrives on an interface\n2. Router extracts the destination IP from the IP header\n3. Router performs a **longest prefix match** lookup in the routing table\n4. If a match is found, forward out the indicated interface (possibly with ARP for next-hop MAC)\n5. If no match and a default route exists, forward to the default gateway\n6. If no match and no default route, drop the packet (send ICMP Destination Unreachable)\n\n### The Routing Table\n\nEvery router maintains a routing table populated by three sources:\n\n**Connected routes (C):** Automatically added when an interface is configured with an IP and is up/up. Administrative Distance = 0.\n\n**Static routes (S):** Manually configured by a network administrator. AD = 1. Simple but does not adapt to topology changes.\n\n**Dynamic routes:** Learned automatically from neighbouring routers via a routing protocol. The router exchanges information and calculates best paths.\n\n### Administrative Distance (AD)\n\nWhen multiple sources provide a route to the same destination, the router uses **Administrative Distance** to select the most trusted source. Lower AD wins.\n\n| Source | AD |\n|--------|----|\n| Connected (C) | 0 |\n| Static (S) | 1 |\n| eBGP | 20 |\n| EIGRP (internal) | 90 |\n| OSPF | 110 |\n| RIP | 120 |\n| iBGP | 200 |\n| Unknown / unreachable | 255 |\n\n### Longest Prefix Match\n\nWhen multiple routes match a destination IP, the router selects the most specific — the route with the longest subnet mask (highest prefix length). This is the single most important routing concept.\n\n**Example routing table:**\n```\nC  10.0.0.0/8     is directly connected, Gi0/0\nO  10.0.1.0/24    via 10.0.12.2\nS  10.0.1.50/32   via 10.0.12.3\n```\n\nA packet to **10.0.1.50** matches all three routes. The /32 (host route) wins — longest prefix.\nA packet to **10.0.2.1** matches only 10.0.0.0/8 — that is the only match.\nA packet to **10.0.1.100** matches 10.0.0.0/8 and 10.0.1.0/24 — the /24 wins.\n\n### Routing Protocols Overview\n\n**Distance Vector (RIP):** Routers share their entire routing table with neighbours. Simple, slow to converge, limited to 15 hops. RIPv2 supports VLSM/CIDR. Used only in very small or legacy networks.\n\n**Link State (OSPF):** Each router builds a complete map of the network (LSDB — Link State Database) and runs Dijkstra\'s shortest path algorithm. Fast convergence. Supports VLSM, hierarchical areas, and large networks. AD = 110. The standard IGP for enterprise networks.\n\n**Path Vector (BGP):** Used between autonomous systems on the internet. BGP makes routing decisions based on AS paths, policies, and attributes rather than just metric. eBGP connects different ASes; iBGP connects routers within an AS. Very slow to converge by design — stability over speed.\n\n**EIGRP:** Cisco proprietary (open standard since 2013). Hybrid distance-vector/link-state. Fast convergence, supports unequal-cost load balancing. AD = 90 (internal). Still found in Cisco-heavy enterprise networks.\n\n### Static Routing\n\n```\n! Route to 10.0.2.0/24 via next-hop 10.0.12.2\nip route 10.0.2.0 255.255.255.0 10.0.12.2\n\n! Default route (gateway of last resort)\nip route 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 10.0.12.1\n\n! Floating static (backup route, higher AD than OSPF)\nip route 10.0.2.0 255.255.255.0 10.0.12.3 200\n```\n\n### Default Route\n\nThe default route (0.0.0.0/0) matches any destination not matched by a more specific route. Every stub network (one with a single exit point) needs a default route pointing toward the internet or upstream router. The default route is often called the "gateway of last resort."\n\n### Routing vs Switching\n\n| | Switching (L2) | Routing (L3) |\n|--|----------------|---------------|\n| Address used | MAC address | IP address |\n| Scope | Within a network | Between networks |\n| Table | MAC/CAM table | Routing table |\n| Broadcast | Forwards broadcasts | Stops broadcasts |\n| Loop prevention | STP | TTL field |\n| Protocol | Ethernet | IP |',
  practical_md = E'## Routing in Practice\n\n### Reading the Routing Table\n\n```\nRouter# show ip route\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, O - OSPF, B - BGP\n\nGateway of last resort is 10.0.12.1 to network 0.0.0.0\n\nC    10.0.1.0/24 is directly connected, GigabitEthernet0/0\nC    10.0.12.0/30 is directly connected, GigabitEthernet0/1\nO    10.0.2.0/24 [110/2] via 10.0.12.2, 00:05:44, Gi0/1\nS*   0.0.0.0/0 [1/0] via 10.0.12.1\n```\n\n**Reading the format:** `[AD/metric] via next-hop, age, interface`\n- `[110/2]` = AD 110 (OSPF), metric (cost) of 2\n- `S*` = static default route (gateway of last resort)\n\n### Verifying Connectivity\n\n```\n! Ping a remote host\nping 10.0.2.1\n\n! Extended ping (specify source)\nping 10.0.2.1 source 10.0.1.1\n\n! Traceroute — see each hop\ntraceroute 10.0.2.1\n\n! Check interface IPs and status\nshow ip interface brief\n```\n\n### Troubleshooting Routing\n\n1. `show ip interface brief` — are the interfaces up/up?\n2. `show ip route` — is the destination network in the table?\n3. `ping` the next-hop IP — can you reach the adjacent router?\n4. `traceroute` — where does the packet die?\n5. Check ACLs — `show access-lists`\n6. Check NAT — `show ip nat translations`\n\n### Floating Static Routes\n\nA floating static route has a higher AD than the primary dynamic route. It is dormant while the dynamic route exists, and becomes active only if the dynamic route disappears (link failure):\n\n```\n! Primary path via OSPF (AD 110) — automatic\n! Backup via static (AD 200) — only used if OSPF route gone\nip route 10.0.2.0 255.255.255.0 192.168.2.1 200\n```',
  key_commands = '["show ip route", "show ip interface brief", "ping", "traceroute", "ip route 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 <next-hop>", "ip route <network> <mask> <next-hop>", "show ip route summary"]'::jsonb,
  common_mistakes = '["Forgetting the default route — a router without 0.0.0.0/0 will drop any packet with an unknown destination", "Not understanding longest prefix match — the most specific route always wins", "Confusing Administrative Distance with metric — AD selects the source, metric ranks paths within the same source", "Static routes do not automatically recover from failures — use dynamic protocols or floating statics", "Forgetting that routing table entries require the interface to be up/up — a route via a down interface is withdrawn"]'::jsonb
WHERE topic_id = (SELECT id FROM topics WHERE slug = 'routing-fundamentals');

-- 7. How The Internet Works
UPDATE topic_content SET
  osi_layer = 'All Layers',
  theory_md = E'## How The Internet Works\n\nThe internet appears instantaneous — you type a URL and a page appears in milliseconds. Behind the scenes, a precisely orchestrated series of protocols spanning every OSI layer makes this possible. Understanding the full end-to-end journey reveals how all the networking concepts fit together.\n\n### Step 1 — DNS Resolution\n\nBefore your browser can connect to `www.example.com`, it needs an IP address. Your OS checks:\n1. Local DNS cache (previously resolved)\n2. Hosts file (`/etc/hosts` or `C:\\Windows\\System32\\drivers\\etc\\hosts`)\n3. Recursive DNS resolver (usually your ISP or a public resolver like 8.8.8.8)\n\nThe recursive resolver performs a full resolution if not cached — querying root nameservers, then TLD nameservers (.com), then the authoritative nameserver for example.com. The final answer (an A or AAAA record) is returned and cached for the TTL duration.\n\n### Step 2 — TCP Three-Way Handshake\n\nWith the IP address known, your browser initiates a TCP connection to port 443 (HTTPS) or 80 (HTTP):\n\n1. **SYN:** Client sends SYN packet with initial sequence number (ISN)\n2. **SYN-ACK:** Server acknowledges, sends its own ISN\n3. **ACK:** Client acknowledges — connection established\n\nThis takes one round-trip time (RTT). For a server 50ms away, the handshake alone costs 100ms before any data flows.\n\n### Step 3 — TLS Handshake (HTTPS)\n\nAfter TCP is established, TLS negotiates encryption:\n1. **ClientHello:** Browser sends supported cipher suites and TLS version\n2. **ServerHello + Certificate:** Server picks cipher, sends X.509 certificate\n3. **Key Exchange:** Diffie-Hellman exchange establishes session keys\n4. **Finished:** Both sides confirm encrypted channel is ready\n\nTLS 1.3 reduces this to 1 RTT (vs 2 RTT for TLS 1.2). QUIC (HTTP/3) combines TCP+TLS into a single 0-RTT or 1-RTT handshake.\n\n### Step 4 — NAT at Your Router\n\nYour PC has a private IP (e.g. 192.168.1.10). Your home router performs NAT/PAT — replacing your private source IP with its public IP and creating a translation entry. Return traffic hits the router, which reverses the translation and delivers it to your PC.\n\n### Step 5 — BGP Routing Across the Internet\n\nPackets leave your ISP and traverse the internet via BGP (Border Gateway Protocol). The internet is composed of ~80,000 autonomous systems (ASes) — each an independently administered network (ISP, cloud provider, university, enterprise). BGP routers exchange reachability information between ASes, enabling end-to-end routing across the globe.\n\nEach router along the path forwards the packet based on longest-prefix-match in its BGP routing table. A packet from Kansas City to a London data centre might traverse 10–15 hops across multiple ISPs.\n\n### Step 6 — HTTP Request and Response\n\nWith the encrypted TCP connection established, the browser sends an HTTP GET request. The server processes it and responds with HTTP status 200 and the HTML/CSS/JS content. TCP ensures reliable, ordered delivery — retransmitting any lost segments.\n\n**HTTP/2** multiplexes multiple requests over a single TCP connection (eliminating head-of-line blocking). **HTTP/3** uses QUIC over UDP for even lower latency.\n\n### Step 7 — Content Delivery Networks (CDN)\n\nMajor websites use CDNs (Cloudflare, Akamai, AWS CloudFront) to cache content at edge nodes close to users. When you resolve `www.example.com`, DNS may return the IP of a CDN edge node 5ms away rather than the origin server 100ms away — dramatically reducing latency.\n\n### Key Concepts Reinforced\n\n**MAC addresses change at every hop.** The IP packet carries 192.168.1.10 → 93.184.216.34 from end to end. But the Ethernet frame\'s MAC addresses change at every router — each router rewrites them with its own MAC and the next-hop MAC.\n\n**IP is end-to-end. MAC is hop-to-hop.** This is the most commonly tested concept in CCNA.\n\n**TTL prevents loops.** Every IP packet has a TTL (Time To Live) field, decremented by 1 at each router. If TTL reaches 0, the packet is dropped and an ICMP Time Exceeded is sent back. Traceroute exploits this to map the path.\n\n### End-to-End Summary\n\n| Step | Protocol | OSI Layer |\n|------|----------|-----------|\n| DNS resolution | DNS / UDP | 7 / 4 |\n| TCP handshake | TCP | 4 |\n| TLS negotiation | TLS | 6 |\n| NAT translation | IP rewrite | 3 |\n| Internet routing | BGP / IP | 3 |\n| HTTP request | HTTP/2 | 7 |\n| Ethernet framing | 802.3 | 2 |\n| Physical bits | Copper/fibre | 1 |',
  practical_md = E'## Tracing the Full Path\n\n### Using traceroute\n\nTraceroute reveals every router hop between you and a destination:\n\n```\ntraceroute google.com\n\n 1  192.168.1.1      1ms   (your home router)\n 2  10.20.30.1       8ms   (ISP first hop)\n 3  72.14.215.1     15ms   (ISP backbone)\n 4  209.85.252.1    18ms   (Google edge)\n 5  google.com      20ms   (destination)\n```\n\nAsterisks (***) mean that router does not respond to ICMP TTL-exceeded — this is normal for security-hardened routers and does not mean the path is broken.\n\n### DNS Verification\n\n```bash\n# Check what IP a hostname resolves to\nnslookup www.google.com\n\n# Detailed DNS query\ndig www.google.com\n\n# Check which DNS server your system uses\ncat /etc/resolv.conf  (Linux)\nipconfig /all         (Windows — look for DNS Servers)\n```\n\n### TCP Connectivity Testing\n\n```bash\n# Test if a TCP port is open\ntelnet 93.184.216.34 443\nnc -zv 93.184.216.34 443\n\n# From a Cisco router — extended ping\nping 8.8.8.8 repeat 100 size 1400\n```\n\n### Viewing NAT Translations\n\n```\nRouter# show ip nat translations\nPro  Inside global       Inside local        Outside\ntcp  203.0.113.1:1234   192.168.1.10:1234   93.184.216.34:443\n```\n\n### Common Real-World Scenarios\n\n**"Can ping IP but not hostname"** → DNS problem (L7). Check DNS server config.\n**"Can ping gateway but not beyond"** → Routing or NAT problem at the edge.\n**"Intermittent connectivity"** → Check for packet loss with extended ping, check for route flapping with `debug ip routing`.\n**"Slow but connected"** → Bandwidth saturation, high RTT, or retransmissions (TCP).',
  key_commands = '["traceroute", "ping", "show ip nat translations", "show ip route", "debug ip packet", "nslookup", "dig"]'::jsonb,
  common_mistakes = '["Thinking the Internet is one network — it is ~80,000 autonomous systems connected via BGP", "Assuming IP addresses change at each hop — only MAC addresses change, IPs stay end-to-end", "Forgetting DNS is the first thing that happens — if DNS fails, nothing else works", "Ignoring TTL — every IP packet has a TTL that limits how many hops it can traverse", "Thinking NAT is only on home routers — enterprises use NAT at WAN edge too"]'::jsonb
WHERE topic_id = (SELECT id FROM topics WHERE slug = 'how-internet-works');

-- 8. Network Layer Architecture (TCP/IP model + hierarchical design)
UPDATE topic_content SET
  osi_layer = 'All Layers',
  theory_md = E'## Network Layer Architecture\n\nThis topic covers two complementary architectural frameworks that every network engineer must understand: the **TCP/IP protocol stack** (how data is structured and transmitted) and the **Cisco hierarchical network model** (how enterprise networks are physically and logically designed).\n\n### The TCP/IP Model\n\nThe TCP/IP model is the practical framework underlying the internet and virtually all modern networks. It maps to a subset of the OSI layers:\n\n| TCP/IP Layer | OSI Equivalent | Key Protocols |\n|--------------|---------------|---------------|\n| Application | Layers 5, 6, 7 | HTTP, HTTPS, DNS, SMTP, DHCP, SSH, FTP, SNMP |\n| Transport | Layer 4 | TCP, UDP |\n| Internet | Layer 3 | IP (v4/v6), ICMP, ARP, IPsec |\n| Network Access | Layers 1, 2 | Ethernet, Wi-Fi (802.11), PPP, Frame Relay |\n\n### TCP vs UDP\n\nThe Transport layer offers two fundamentally different services:\n\n**TCP (Transmission Control Protocol):**\n- Connection-oriented — three-way handshake before data\n- Reliable — acknowledgements, retransmission of lost segments\n- Ordered — sequence numbers ensure correct reassembly\n- Flow control — receiver advertises window size\n- Slower than UDP due to overhead\n- Use: HTTP/S, SSH, FTP, SMTP, database queries\n\n**UDP (User Datagram Protocol):**\n- Connectionless — no handshake, no acknowledgement\n- Unreliable — lost packets are not retransmitted\n- Fast — minimal overhead\n- Application handles any reliability needs\n- Use: DNS, DHCP, VoIP, video streaming, SNMP, TFTP\n\n### IP Addressing and Encapsulation\n\nAt the Internet (L3) layer, data is encapsulated in an **IP packet** with source and destination IP addresses. These IPs remain constant end-to-end across the entire path.\n\nAt the Network Access (L2) layer, the packet is encapsulated in a **frame** with source and destination MAC addresses. MACs change at every hop — each router replaces them with the addresses for the next segment.\n\n**PDU Names by Layer:**\n\n| Layer | PDU | Key Fields |\n|-------|-----|------------|\n| Application | Message / Data | Application-specific |\n| Transport | Segment (TCP) / Datagram (UDP) | Src/Dst port, seq/ack |\n| Internet | Packet | Src/Dst IP, TTL, protocol |\n| Network Access | Frame | Src/Dst MAC, EtherType, FCS |\n\n### The Cisco Three-Tier Hierarchical Model\n\nFor enterprise networks, Cisco developed a three-tier hierarchical design model that separates network functions into distinct layers:\n\n**Access Layer:**\n- Connects end devices: PCs, IP phones, printers, wireless APs\n- Provides port density (many ports)\n- Enforces security: 802.1X, port security, DHCP snooping, DAI\n- Assigns devices to VLANs\n- PoE for phones and APs\n- Devices: access switches (Catalyst 2960/9200)\n\n**Distribution Layer:**\n- Aggregates access layer switches\n- Inter-VLAN routing (SVIs or ROAS)\n- Policy enforcement: QoS, ACLs, route summarisation\n- Redundant uplinks to core (partial mesh)\n- HSRP/VRRP for gateway redundancy\n- Devices: multilayer switches (Catalyst 3850/9300)\n\n**Core Layer:**\n- High-speed backbone — connects distribution blocks and WAN/DC\n- No policy enforcement — speed is the priority\n- Full or partial mesh for maximum redundancy\n- Sub-millisecond failover\n- Devices: high-capacity switches/routers (Catalyst 9500/9600, Nexus)\n\n### Two-Tier (Collapsed Core)\n\nSmaller enterprise networks merge the distribution and core layers:\n- Reduces cost and complexity\n- Suitable for single-building or small campus\n- Distribution switches take on core responsibilities\n- Trade-off: less scalability\n\n### Spine-Leaf (Data Centre)\n\nModern data centres use spine-leaf architecture:\n- **Leaf switches:** Connect servers. Every leaf connects to every spine.\n- **Spine switches:** Backbone — connect all leaves, never to each other.\n- Predictable east-west traffic latency (always 2 hops server-to-server)\n- Horizontally scalable — add leaf or spine switches as needed\n- Supports ECMP for load balancing across multiple spine paths\n\n### Protocol Stack Example: HTTP Request\n\n```\nApplication:  GET /index.html HTTP/2 (port 443)\nTransport:    TCP Segment [Src:52341 Dst:443 Seq:1001 Ack:501]\nInternet:     IP Packet [Src:10.0.1.10 Dst:93.184.216.34 TTL:64]\nNetwork Access: Ethernet Frame [Src:aa:bb Dst:cc:dd EtherType:0x0800]\nPhysical:     Electrical signals on Cat6 copper\n```\n\nAt the destination server, each layer strips its header and passes data up — decapsulation — until the application receives the HTTP request.',
  practical_md = E'## Architecture in Practice\n\n### Identifying PDUs with Wireshark\n\nWireshark labels captured traffic by protocol layer. An HTTP capture shows:\n- Frame (L2): Ethernet II, Src MAC, Dst MAC\n- IPv4 (L3): Source IP, Destination IP, TTL\n- TCP (L4): Source Port, Destination Port, Seq/Ack\n- HTTP (L7): GET /path, Host header\n\n### Cisco IOS — Verifying the Stack\n\n```\n! L3 — IP addresses\nshow ip interface brief\n\n! L2 — MAC table\nshow mac address-table\n\n! L4 — active TCP connections (on router/IOS-XE)\nshow tcp brief\n\n! L1/L2 — physical and protocol status\nshow interfaces Gi0/0\n\n! Full neighbour discovery (reveals adjacent devices)\nshow cdp neighbors detail\n```\n\n### Hierarchical Design Verification\n\n```\n! Verify inter-VLAN routing via SVIs (distribution layer)\nshow ip route\nshow interfaces vlan 10\n\n! Verify HSRP redundancy (distribution layer)\nshow standby brief\n\n! Verify trunk links (access to distribution)\nshow interfaces trunk\n\n! Verify spanning-tree (per VLAN)\nshow spanning-tree vlan 10\n```\n\n### Architecture Decision Framework\n\n- **< 200 users, single building:** Two-tier collapsed core\n- **200–2000 users, single campus:** Three-tier hierarchical\n- **Data centre:** Spine-leaf\n- **WAN/multi-site:** Hub-and-spoke (MPLS) or SD-WAN mesh\n- **Cloud-first:** Zero-trust, microsegmentation, no traditional perimeter',
  key_commands = '["show ip interface brief", "show interfaces", "show mac address-table", "show ip route", "show standby brief", "show interfaces trunk", "show spanning-tree", "show cdp neighbors detail"]'::jsonb,
  common_mistakes = '["Confusing the TCP/IP model (4 layers) with OSI (7 layers) — TCP/IP is what is actually implemented", "Thinking IP addresses change at each hop — only MAC addresses change", "Designing flat networks (single VLAN) for large deployments — use hierarchical design", "Putting policy enforcement at the core layer — core is for speed, policy belongs at distribution", "Forgetting that spine-leaf is for data centre east-west traffic, not traditional campus networks"]'::jsonb
WHERE topic_id = (SELECT id FROM topics WHERE slug = 'network-layer-arch');

